Manganese-leonite is found in three forms: \begin{itemize} \item A \href{current_web_home_dir/A8B2CD12E2_mP100_14_8e_2e_ab_12e_2e-001}{low-temperature structure}, stable below 168K. \item This \href{current_web_home_dir/A8B2CD12E2_mC200_15_8f_2f_ae_2e11f_2f-001}{intermediate-temperature structure}, stable in between 168 and 205K. \item The \href{current_web_home_dir/A8B2CD15E2_mC112_12_2i3j_j_ac_g4i5j_2i-001}{room temperature structure, {\em Strukturbericht} $H4_{23}$}, stable above 205K. \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.25in} 
 The current structure orders all of the SO$_{4}$ radicals. The data was taken from a sample held at 185K. 
 (Hertweck, 2001) give crystallographic information of the 185K phase in the $I2/a$ setting of space group \#15, with the origin supposedly shifted by $(\frac14,\frac14,\frac12)$ from the -1 point on the $a$-glide plane (\href{http://img.chem.ucl.ac.uk/sgp/large/015gy1.htm}{the symmetry operations for this setting may be found here}).  We were unable to use their data to construct a realistic crystal structure.  Instead, we used the interpretation of their results by (Villars, 2016) to put the structure in the standard $C2/c$ setting of space group \#15. Unfortunately this does not agree with the ICSD entry.  We are investigating further and will update this page when we have more information.
